					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    The Tailoring Guide (From Patchwork to Studded)</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Jessy Wolvespirit</a> | 
		            12/7/1999 3:30:35 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">   I hear you're interested in learning how to make armor. 'How do I do it?' you ask. Well, let me tell you a bit about tailoring:<BR>
First of All, you must purchase some patterns and a tailoring kit (large is best but small will do for now) from your local Tailoring Shoppe.<BR>
---------------------------------- <BR>
PART ONE: Patchwork Armor<BR>
Take a Ruined Cat, Bear or Wolf Pelt from an animal found in almost any zone and place it in the kit, take one of the patterns you bought (the pattern for the type of armor you want to make) and place it inside the kit too. Press Combine, if you fail it will tell you so and the pelt and the pattern will be lost. If you succeed, you will be holding a brand new piece of patchwork armor. Patchwork Armor is wearable by everyone except Necromancers, Wizards, Enchanters, and Magicians.<BR>
-----------------------------------<BR>
PART TWO: Raw Silk<BR>
Well, we all know of those pesky Spiders that hang out near the human towns right? thought so. Anyway, the silk from the larger spiders can be combined in sets of two to form swatches. These swatches are used to make raw silk armor. You take a silk swatch (two for pants or a robe) and combine it with the pattern of the desired piece and voila! you have yourself a genuine piece of armor for your caster friends(Wizards, Enchanters, Magicians, Necromancers)that cannot wear patchwork(and the monks who are too stubborn to wear it though they can). You will need a large sewing kit to make the pants and/or the robe(s) because you need to plae the swatches in the kit seperatley(not stacked).<BR>
----------------------------------<BR>
PART THREE: Cured Silk<BR>
Now, Cured Silk is a magical armor for monks only. It can be made by combining a certain number of Heady Kiolas (2 kiola saps + 1 water flask + 1 bottle combined in a brewing barrel) and a certain number of the Silk Swatches used in Raw Silk. The recipes I know are as follows:<BR>
Mask- 1 silk swatch, 1 heady kiola, and the mask pattern.<BR>
Collar- 1 silk swatch, 2 heady kiola, and the gorget pattern.<BR>
Mantle- 2 silk swatches, 2 heady kiola, and the shoulderpad pattern.<BR>
Cloak- 2 silk swatches, 2 heady kiola, and the cloak pattern.<BR>
Sleeves- 2 silk swatches, 2 heady kiola, and the sleeve pattern.<BR>
Gloves- 2 silk swatches, 2 heady kiola, and the glove pattern.<BR>
Sandals- 1 silk swatch, 2 heady kiola, and the boot pattern.<BR>
Gi- 3 silk swatches, 2 heady kiola, and the tunic pattern.<BR>
Leggings- 2 silk swatches, 3 heady kiola, and the pant pattern.<BR>
Wristbands- 1 swatch, 2 heady kiola, and the wristband pattern.<BR>
(Most pieces of cured silk have an armor class one higher than raw silk.) <BR>
----------------------------------<BR>
PART FOUR: Studded Leather<BR>
Studded leather is the upgrade to patchwork. You use the same technique except you use Medium Quality (Cat, Bear or Wolf) Pelts instead of ruined ones, in addition, you need metal studs which can be created through blacksmithing.<BR>
<BR>
You need 1 stud for masks. 2 studs for Gorgets, Belts, and Bracers. 3 studs for Caps, Shoulderpads, and Sleeves. 4 studs for Cloaks, Gloves, Pants and Boots. 5 studs for Tunics.<BR>
-----------------------------------<BR>
PART FIVE: Reinforced Leather Armor<BR>
for Reinforced Leather Armor you need the patterns, large sewing kit, High Quality Pelts, and Reinforced Steel boning. Steel Boning can be made through Blacksmithing. You need 1 steel boning for Mask, Gorget and Bracers. 2 steel boning for Cap, Shoulderpads, Cloak, Sleeves, and Gloves. 3 steel boning  for Boots and Pants. 4 steel boning for Tunics.<BR>
Enjoy!
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
